<br>
I sold much of my berserker's equipment in order to loan some money to a friend; it worked out well since my zerker had basically been collecting dust since I started a healer... unfortunately, my friend hasn't played lately, and hasn't even come close to making the money the owes me, and I've grown bored to death with my healer, so I decided to try something new.<br>
<br>
Last night I started a paladin on Lancelot, who's almost to level 8 now, and one thing I've noticed is that for some reason, I've having a helluva time keeping my paladin's gear up to date.<br>
<br>
I'm currently using my guild-gift greatsword, which, although yellow, has significantly lower damage output than other yellow 2-handed weapons the merchants sell. I've got about half a suit of iron bone-studded armor, and the other half is rawhide siluric leather; I'm about half yellow, half blue... I know that many tanks keep themselves outfitted in yellow armor with an orange weapon, and I'm just curious how this is possible (or if it's possible at all) without twinking; I was spoiled with my zerker, and had a friend who'd been playing for a long time basically give me all hand-me-down equipment, and I was almost always decked out in orange, and up until my healer was wearing chain, money was never a problem... my lowbie hero on Palimodes has somehow managed to keep yellow armor with an orange weapon without outside help, but that's only because the waterbugs provided such an excellent source of income.<br>
<br>
I'm really having fun trying all these new classes know; I've got a ton of characters right around or slightly above level 10 from all different sorts of classes, and I'm finding I like the tanks best... it's just getting so damned frustrating trying to keep myself in good gear, listening to so-and-so who plays the same class at the same level talk about soloing yellows when I can't even think about doing that, and it's espcially irritating when some blue theurgist runs by and spamcasts his pets at something that cons yellow or orange to me, and then runs on to kill the next thing...<br>
<br>
*sigh* Anyways, I'm rambling. Just... how do you guys do it? <p>--For every winner, there are dozens of losers. Odds are you're one of 'em. 
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uexquisitesin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Exquisitesin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(1/7/02 6:51:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovefrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=251.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Money and melee</span><hr size=1> I have two suggestions:<br>
<br>
1.) Set aside a few hours where you decide not to concentrate on levelling, but instead solo greens.<br>
<br>
2.) Try and fight in places that aren't itemized. I don't know where that is at your level, but I make a lot of coin in such places, so I guess it transfers <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ubrairwolf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Brairwolf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(1/7/02 6:54:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovefrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=251.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Money and melee</span><hr size=1> Differnt mobs drop different amount of cash.  Since I don't play in mid I can't tell you the money makers.  However one thing that is true if you need money stick to killing blues or greens unless you find a nice money maker higher con.  Why blues and greens?  You make less exp but you still get the items and coin they drop.  So your gear is still effective vs them for longer.  Yellow and higher cons give you lots more exp but the cash per kill is not as much on average. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/unyssarainwhisper.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Nyssa Rainwhisper</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://arnemetia.homestead.com/files/MiscImages/bluepawbullet.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(1/8/02 5:54:10 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovefrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=251.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://arnemetia.homestead.com/files/MiscImages/zidane.gif WIDTH=64 HEIGHT=64></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Money and melee</span><hr size=1> One word: (well, technically 2 words) tradeskills.  While my main character is not a melee class, I still wear scale armor just like a melee class, and since I'm a healer, I pretty much tank like a melee class anyways. ;)<br>
<br>
As an armor crafter, I netted 400g doing commissions from 300 skill to 650 skill. (I spent approx 15-20g getting to 300 skill.) If you just want the money, you don't have to go beyond 650 skill.  400g should last you a while. :) <p><CENTER>
